Subject: Re: [T2] oil pressure switch sealing

On Thu, Aug 12, 2004 at 11:13:31AM -0500, Gary G. Martin wrote:
>     The oil pressure switch has a special kind of thread called  "pipe
> threads". Pipe threads are not like machine threads. Pipe threads are
> tapered. That means, the first threads are really shallow and the first part
> peaks of the threads do not reach all the way to the bottoms of the valleys
> of the female pipe threads. However, as you get to the other end of the pipe
> threads, they get "longer" or "taller" . 

This isn't exactly correct either. NPT has all threads cut the same
depth. The difference is that they are cut on (or into) the piece at a
taper. A very exagerated view of this is a pencil point when
sharpened. It was cut at a taper. The threads just follow this taper.

